      <p>You don't need to spend a fortune to get good lighting on a construction site. Some of the brightest, most durable job site lights on Amazon cost well under $100 — and they deliver the same LED technology, IP weather ratings, and lumen output as lights costing twice as much.</p>
      <p>The key is knowing which budget lights are actually built to survive a job site. We've sorted through the reviews, ratings, and real-world feedback from contractors to find the most affordable work lights that still deliver professional-grade performance. Here are the best budget job site lights you can buy right now.</p>

      <h2>What to Look for in Budget Job Site Lights</h2>
      <p>When you're shopping under $100, you need to prioritize the features that actually matter for construction work:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>LED technology is non-negotiable.</strong> At any price point, LED outperforms halogen in efficiency, lifespan, and durability. Never buy a halogen work light in 2026 — even budget LEDs are better.</li>
        <li><strong>Look for 5000K daylight color temperature.</strong> Cheaper lights sometimes use warm-white LEDs (2700–3000K) meant for home use. These are terrible for job sites because they distort colors and make it hard to see details. Insist on 5000K.</li>
        <li><strong>Check the IP rating.</strong> For outdoor or dusty job sites, IP65 is the minimum. Indoor-only lights without IP ratings are cheaper but won't survive moisture or dust.</li>
        <li><strong>Read reviews for durability.</strong> The biggest risk with budget lights is that they break after a few drops. Look for reviews mentioning drops, bumps, and job site abuse.</li>
        <li><strong>Cord length matters.</strong> Budget lights sometimes come with short cords to save money. Look for at least 5–10 feet of cord, and check whether extension cords are compatible.</li>
      </ul>

