      <h2>Can You Really Get Quality Job Site Lights Under $100?</h2>
      <p>Absolutely — but you need to be strategic. The budget lighting market in 2026 is excellent because LED technology has become so cheap to manufacture. A $50 LED work light in 2026 outperforms a $150 halogen light from 2015 in every measurable category: brightness, efficiency, durability, and lifespan.</p>
      <p>Here's what you trade off at lower price points:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Build materials —</strong> Budget lights use high-impact plastic instead of aluminum or steel housings. Plastic is lighter and still durable, but it won't survive being run over by a truck like a metal housing might.</li>
        <li><strong>Shorter cords —</strong> Budget lights often come with 5–10 foot cords vs. 15–25 feet on premium models. Budget for a quality extension cord.</li>
        <li><strong>No tripod or stand —</strong> The most affordable lights are basic floodlight panels you set on the floor or a workbench. Tripod mounts add cost.</li>
        <li><strong>Warranty —</strong> Premium brands like DEWALT offer multi-year warranties. Budget brands typically offer 1 year or less. At these price points, buying a spare is often cheaper than dealing with a warranty claim.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Tips to Make Budget Job Site Lights Last Longer</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Store them in a protective case.</strong> The biggest killer of budget lights is being tossed loose in a truck bed with tools. A $20 hard case or even a heavy-duty tote bag doubles their lifespan.</li>
        <li><strong>Coil cords properly.</strong> Extension cord damage is the most common failure point. Use a cord reel or tie-wrap straps, not knots.</li>
        <li><strong>Keep them out of standing water.</strong> Even IP65/IP66 rated lights have limits. Don't submerge them or leave them in puddles overnight.</li>
        <li><strong>Wipe lenses clean.</strong> Mud and drywall dust on the lens cuts light output by 30–50%. A quick wipe with a dry cloth restores full brightness.</li>
        <li><strong>Buy an extra one.</strong> At $50–$70 per light, keeping a spare in the truck is cheaper than losing an hour of crew time because a light failed mid-shift.</li>
      </ul>

